HIGH|internal/astgroup/host.go:197|wasmParser.Parse indexes res[0] (alloc result) and pr[0] (parse result) with no length check on the returned slices. wazero sizes the result slice to the guest function's declared result count, so an override-dir .wasm whose alloc or parse exports zero results makes res[0]/pr[0] panic with index-out-of-range, crashing the reconcile gate that host.go:50-53 promises will degrade, not crash. WithOverrideDir is explicitly the untrusted drop-in path.|In host.go Parse, guard len(res)==0 and len(pr)==0 before indexing and return an error (Node{}, fmt.Errorf). Add a unit test instantiating a stub module whose alloc returns no results and assert an error, not a panic.|error-handling|30|internal/astgroup/host.go:193-212|claude
HIGH|internal/astgroup/host.go:206|parse.Call is invoked with p.ctx = context.Background() (host.go:55): no deadline, no interpreter fuel budget. The maxSourceBytes comment (host.go:174-178) claims the 8MiB size cap removes the need for an execution-timeout watchdog, but a size cap bounds input length, not CPU. A pathological input or a hostile override plugin that loops forever hangs parse.Call indefinitely while holding p.mu, permanently wedging every future parse for that language.|Derive a per-call context.WithTimeout and pass it to parse.Call, and/or build the runtime with wazero.NewRuntimeConfig().WithCloseOnContextDone(true). Verify with a spinning test plugin that Parse returns a timeout error rather than hanging.|security|60|internal/astgroup/host.go:54-56,206-209|claude
HIGH|internal/astgroup/cover.go:70|coveringChain increments blockIdx only for block-typed children, and when the covering child is a non-block it returns subChain,subAddr (cover.go:70), discarding the accumulated blockIdx and recomputing descendant indices relative to that wrapper from 0. Two sibling non-block statements each wrapping one identically-shaped anonymous block (e.g. foo(func(){...}) and bar(func(){...}), exprstmt->call->funclit) both yield address segment funclit::0. Identical address + identical Merkle hash collapses two distinct blocks into one key, defeating the sibling-distinguishing guarantee the address was added for.|In coveringChain, carry the parent block-position into the non-block descent (prefix the wrapper's sibling index, or count covering-child position regardless of block-ness) so descendants under distinct non-block siblings get distinct addresses. Test two sibling exprstmts each holding an identical anonymous funclit and assert their CoveringBlock addresses differ.|correctness|120|internal/astgroup/cover.go:50-71|claude
HIGH|internal/astgroup/parsers/build.sh:16|build.sh invokes whatever go is on PATH with no toolchain pin, no minimum-version check, and no GOTOOLCHAIN. The wasm export ABI requires a recent Go; nothing enforces it. The script header (lines 4-6) states it is NOT part of go build or CI, so the committed go.wasm/python.wasm artifacts can drift from their src/ source with zero detection, and -trimpath alone does not make two toolchain versions byte-reproducible.|Pin the toolchain (GOTOOLCHAIN=go1.24.x) and assert go version at the top of build.sh. Add a CI job that runs build.sh then git diff --exit-code on the .wasm files so source/binary drift fails the build.|testing|120|internal/astgroup/parsers/build.sh:4-24|claude
HIGH|internal/reconcile/astgrouping.go:27|The opt-out is gated on os.Getenv(astGroupingDisabledEnv) != "", so ANY non-empty value disables AST grouping, including the intuitively-on values ATCR_DISABLE_AST_GROUPING=0 and =false. A user who sets =false to KEEP the adopted primary signal silently reverts to legacy proximity, with no error and no log. For a reversible-adoption escape hatch, truthiness-by-presence is the wrong semantics.|Parse the value with strconv.ParseBool (treat parse failure as not-disabled), or document the var as presence-only. At minimum the doc comment must state that any non-empty value including 0/false disables.|error-handling|15|internal/reconcile/astgrouping.go:26-32|claude
MEDIUM|internal/astgroup/grouper.go:103|treeFor holds the single grouper mutex g.mu across os.ReadFile and parser.Parse (grouper.go:103-125). A wasm parse of a large file can take many ms to seconds; while it runs, every other GroupKey call, including cache hits for unrelated files, blocks on the same mutex. This serializes all parsing across all files and languages, undermining the <10ms repeat-parse NFR and the safe-for-concurrent-use claim under real concurrency.|Release g.mu before the slow read/parse using a per-file in-flight latch (placeholder with its own sync.Once/channel, parse outside the lock, then store), so distinct files parse concurrently and cache hits never wait on an in-progress parse. Verify with a concurrent benchmark across two large files (wall time ~= max not sum).|performance|120|internal/astgroup/grouper.go:102-132|claude
MEDIUM|internal/astgroup/grouper.go:96|GroupKey calls CoveringBlock (tree walk) and MerkleHash(block) (full recursive subtree sha256) on every finding. For N findings mapping to the same covering block, both are recomputed N times. The parsed tree is cached but the key/hash is not, so the dominant per-finding cost is a redundant whole-subtree walk, the opposite of the parse-once caching the package advertises.|Memoize the group key by line within parsedFile (map[int]string), or cache MerkleHash per node/structural-address, so repeated findings in one block reuse the computed hash. Verify with a benchmark over many findings in one large block showing flat per-finding cost.|performance|30|internal/astgroup/grouper.go:83-96|claude
MEDIUM|internal/astgroup/host.go:56|The runtime is created with default config (wazero.NewRuntime, host.go:56): no memory-pages limit. The 8MiB source cap bounds input, not guest heap: a hostile or buggy override plugin can grow linear memory toward wazero's multi-hundred-MiB default ceiling per language instance with nothing capping it. Combined with the no-timeout finding, the override-dir feature has no resource ceiling.|Construct the runtime with wazero.NewRuntimeConfig().WithMemoryLimitPages(n) sized to the parser's real need, at least for override-loaded modules. Verify a test plugin allocating beyond the limit fails gracefully rather than ballooning host RSS.|security|30|internal/astgroup/host.go:54-65|claude
MEDIUM|internal/astgroup/grouper.go:117|treeFor caches a negative result for any os.ReadFile error (grouper.go:117-120) and never retries. Transient failures (file mid-write, momentary EMFILE, a lock) are conflated with permanent ones, so a file briefly unreadable during a reconcile is pinned ungroupable for the whole run even after it becomes readable. The comment justifies negative caching only for genuinely bad files.|Distinguish permanent failures (parse error, not-exist, path-escape) which deserve negative caching from transient I/O errors which should not be cached (or use a short-lived negative entry). Test a reader that returns EAGAIN once then succeeds and assert the second GroupKey groups.|error-handling|30|internal/astgroup/grouper.go:110-131|claude
MEDIUM|internal/astgroup/parsers/src/goparser/main.go:107|structural() returns true only for ast.Decl, ast.Stmt, and FuncLit. TypeSpec implements ast.Spec NOT ast.Decl, so it never passes the filter in the ast.Inspect walk. The TypeSpec case in nodeKind (line 124) and nodeName (line 139) is dead code: the type kind is never emitted by the Go parser, so a type Foo struct only surfaces as the wrapping gendecl block and the per-type block granularity in cover.go blockKinds is silently lost for Go.|Add TypeSpec (and likely ValueSpec if value-level blocks are wanted) to the structural() switch, or remove the dead type cases and document that Go groups types at gendecl granularity. Add a host test asserting type Foo struct{...} produces a type node.|correctness|60|internal/astgroup/parsers/src/goparser/main.go:107-142|claude
MEDIUM|internal/astgroup/embed.go:5|go:embed pulls in pre-compiled go.wasm and python.wasm that the host compiles and executes (host.go:128-134) with no checksum, signature, or provenance verification, and per build.sh no CI rebuilds them from source. A tampered or stale committed binary passes code review (reviewers read src/*.go, not the opaque .wasm) and ships undetected.|Commit a SHA256SUMS manifest next to the .wasm files, regenerate it in build.sh, and verify it in CI (combined with the rebuild-diff). This makes the binary a verifiable function of the reviewed source.|security|60|internal/astgroup/embed.go:5-15|claude
MEDIUM|internal/astgroup/parsers/src/pyparser/main.go:178|isHeader declares any line ending in ':' (after a naive #-strip and right-trim) a block opener. Multi-line dict/slice/annotation expressions trip this: data = {, a line "key":, or a slice x = arr[1: get treated as a compound-statement header and the following more-indented physical lines attach as a spurious child block. Since structure drives the Merkle hash and CoveringBlock, this silently fabricates blocks and can mis-group findings with no error surfaced.|Tighten isHeader to fire only when the line's first token is in compoundKeywords (require classify to return a compound kind) instead of trusting a trailing colon on arbitrary lines. Add fixtures for multi-line dict and slice.|error-handling|60|internal/astgroup/parsers/src/pyparser/main.go:153-182|claude
MEDIUM|internal/astgroup/parsers/src/pyparser/main.go:112|scanTripleQuotes and stripComment are quote/escape-unaware. A triple-quote appearing inside a # comment, or a # appearing inside a string literal, flips the multi-line-string state machine the wrong way, so arbitrary spans of real code get classified as string content and dropped from significantLines, silently erasing blocks. The heuristic disclaimer documents the risk but does not bound it: on unusual source the structural hash diverges from the true AST.|Run scanTripleQuotes only over the code portion (skip after an unquoted #) and skip triple-quotes occurring inside single-line strings. Add regression fixtures: a # containing a triple-quote, and a string literal containing #.|security|120|internal/astgroup/parsers/src/pyparser/main.go:112-136|claude
MEDIUM|reconcile/cluster.go:69|ClusterWith (in grouper.go) removes keyed findings from the line stream before running proximity on the unkeyed remainder. A finding that covers no AST node (empty key) at line 11 is isolated even though its proximity neighbors at lines 10 and 12 were pulled into a keyed cluster, so a duplicate pair straddling the keyed/unkeyed split that proximity-only would have compared and merged is never compared. AST grouping can REDUCE merges relative to the legacy path; the astgrouping.go:24-25 claim that it can only refine, never break, is false.|Either run proximity over the full line set as well and union the keyed/proximity memberships, or downgrade the doc claim to the truth. Add a test for the keyed/unkeyed-neighbor split case.|correctness|60|reconcile/grouper.go:49-69|claude
MEDIUM|reconcile/cluster.go:66|cluster.go:14-19 advertises that proximity keeps the dedup comparison set bounded (a 3-line window) so DedupeCluster never blows up. AST grouping discards that: every finding inside one large function shares a MerkleHash and collapses into a single cluster regardless of line distance, and dedupeCluster then does pairwise PROBLEM-similarity over the whole group (reconcile.go:81-82). A 200-finding hotspot in one function goes from bounded windows to one O(n^2) cluster, the exact failure the proximity design avoided.|Cap keyed-cluster size before handing to dedupeCluster (fall back to proximity within an over-large keyed group), or document the new worst-case and confirm dedupeCluster is sub-quadratic. Add a stress test with many findings in one block.|performance|60|reconcile/grouper.go:60-68|claude
MEDIUM|internal/reconcile/gate.go:243|A fresh Grouper, and thus a fresh wazero runtime (NewHost) with empty parser/tree caches, is constructed on every RunReconcile call and closed at function exit (gate.go defer closeGrouper). In the long-lived MCP server every reconcile request pays full WASI instantiation plus CompileModule/InstantiateModule for each language again; the compiled-module cache the Host comment touts (host.go:23-27) is thrown away between calls and never amortized across requests.|Hoist the Host (or whole Grouper) to a process-lifetime singleton owned by the MCP engine/CLI, guarded by its existing mutex, and reuse across RunReconcile calls. Keep per-run isolation only for the file-tree cache if staleness is a concern.|performance|120|internal/reconcile/gate.go:238-247|claude
MEDIUM|internal/astgroup/grouper.go:113|Every failure mode in treeFor (path escape, read error, parser load failure, parse error) is swallowed and cached as a silent negative; astGrouperFor and Close discard errors too. If the embedded parsers fail to load wholesale, or Root points at the wrong tree, the adopted primary signal silently degrades to 100% proximity with zero diagnostic output: the operator believes they have AST grouping but get none, indistinguishable from a clean run.|Surface at least a one-line warning/metric when AST grouping yields zero keyed clusters over a run that had parseable-language findings, or thread a debug writer into the grouper so degradation is observable. Do not promote a primary signal that can become a complete no-op invisibly.|maintainability|60|internal/astgroup/grouper.go:102-132|claude
